In Series #2, we built a declarative Config-Driven UI engine that parses JSON schemas and dynamically builds structural layouts. However, a major architectural roadblock inevitably emerges when dealing with thousands of enterprise clients: bundle bloat and dependency sprawl.
If Bank A requires an intricate candlestick charting module, Bank B requires a specialized document validation scanner, and Bank C requires a sprawling regulatory reporting wizard, your static application bundle will quickly balloon into a multi-megabyte monster.
[ Static Bundle Approach ] ──► ( Includes ALL Tenant Components ) ──► 🚨 Massive Bundle Size (15MB+Forcing Bank A to download code exclusively written for Banks B and C degrades performance and compromises isolation. To maintain a lean footprint, your frontend engine must decouple components from the core build.
This article covers how to design a production-grade Runtime Component Registry capable of dynamically resolving, code-splitting, and executing isolated React components on demand.
The Registry Blueprint: Static vs. Dynamic Resolution
A primitive registry relies on static imports. While this handles basic code-splitting via React.lazy, it still requires every component to be declared inside your primary repository and compiled within your central deployment pipeline.
TypeScript
// ❌ The Monolithic Registry: Requires everything at compile-time
import { lazy } from 'react';
export const StaticRegistry = {
'component.bank-a-chart': lazy(() => import('./premium/BankAChart')),
'component.bank-b-scanner': lazy(() => import('./premium/BankBScanner')),
};An enterprise-grade Runtime Component Registry treats components as decoupled plug-ins. The core application exposes an extension canvas, and components are dynamically resolved at runtime from an isolated micro-frontend bucket or edge CDN.
