}2. Implementing the Runtime Engine & Loader
To inject remote code into a running React application without compromising the stability of the thread, we build an asynchronous loader engine. This engine handles script fetching, styling side-effects, and safely mounts modules onto our core application.
TypeScript
// RuntimeComponentRegistry.ts
import React from 'react';
export interface ComponentMetadata {
id: string;
entry: string;
css?: string;
sri?: string;
}
type ComponentMap = Map<string, React.ComponentType<any>>;
class RuntimeComponentRegistry {
private registeredComponents: ComponentMap = new Map();
private loadingPromises: Map<string, Promise<React.ComponentType<any>>> = new Map();
/**
* Registers a component instance directly into the internal cache
*/
public register(id: string, component: React.ComponentType<any>) {
this.registeredComponents.set(id, component);
}
/**
* Resolves a component from cache, or fetches it dynamically from a remote asset bundle
*/
public async resolve(meta: ComponentMetadata): Promise<React.ComponentType<any>> {
if (this.registeredComponents.has(meta.id)) {
return this.registeredComponents.get(meta.id)!;
}
if (this.loadingPromises.has(meta.id)) {
return this.loadingPromises.get(meta.id)!;
}
const loadPromise = this.loadRemoteScript(meta);
this.loadingPromises.set(meta.id, loadPromise);
return loadPromise;
}
private async loadRemoteScript(meta: ComponentMetadata): Promise<React.ComponentType<any>> {
try {
// Inject CSS dependencies if they are explicitly declared
if (meta.css) {
this.injectStylesheet(meta.css);
}
// Modern Module Federation / Native ESM Import
// In 2026, browsers natively handle dynamic imports via ECMAScript modules (ESM)
const module = await import(/* @vite-ignore */ meta.entry); // Expecting a default export or an explicit register call from the remote script
const component = module.default || module.Component;
if (!component) {
throw new Error(`Module loaded from ${meta.entry} does not expose a valid React component export.`);
}
this.registeredComponents.set(meta.id, component);
return component;
} catch (error) {
console.error(`Runtime Registry failure loading component: ${meta.id}`, error);
throw error;
} finally {
this.loadingPromises.delete(meta.id);
}
}
private injectStylesheet(href: string) {
if (document.querySelector(`link[href="${href}"]`)) return;
const link = document.createElement('link');
link.rel = 'stylesheet';
link.href = href;
document.head.appendChild(link);
}
}
export const registryInstance = new RuntimeComponentRegistry();
3. Creating the Wrapper: LazyRemoteComponent
To connect this global loader instance directly with React’s internal rendering lifecycles, we wrap the resolution phase inside a custom lazy execution bridge.
TypeScript
// LazyRemoteComponent.tsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import { registryInstance, ComponentMetadata } from './RuntimeComponentRegistry';interface LazyRemoteComponentProps {
metadata: ComponentMetadata;
componentProps: Record<string, any>;
fallback?: React.ReactNode;
}
export const LazyRemoteComponent: React.FC<LazyRemoteComponentProps> = ({
metadata,
componentProps,
fallback = <div className="h-24 w-full animate-pulse bg-gray-50 rounded" />,
}) => {
const [Component, setComponent] = useState<React.ComponentType<any> | null>(null);
const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);
useEffect(() => {
let isMounted = true;
registryInstance
.resolve(metadata)
.then((resolvedComponent) => {
if (isMounted) setComponent(() => resolvedComponent);
})
.catch((err) => {
if (isMounted) setError(err.message || 'Failed to load remote component');
});
return () => {
isMounted = false;
};
}, [metadata]);
if (error) {
return (
<div className="p-4 border border-red-200 bg-red-50 text-red-700 rounded-md text-sm">
⚠️ <strong>Registry Error:</strong> {error}
</div>
);
}
if (!Component) {
return <>{fallback}</>;
}
return <Component {...componentProps} />;
};
🔒 Crucial Architectural Safeguards
Dynamically introducing remote code into a centralized web core carries major performance and architectural risks. Implement these constraints immediately:
1. Enforce Shared Dependency Contexts
If every single client-specific component downloaded its own isolated instance of react, react-dom, or your core state utility libraries, the host container’s memory footprint would collapse.

• The Solution: Configure your compilation engines (such as Vite or Webpack 5+ Module Federation) to treat core dependencies as external. Remote modules must consume the exact same React context exposed globally on the browser window or through a unified dependency broker.
2. Strict Sandbox Security Policies (SRI & CSP)
Allowing components to load across external CDNs opens up cross-site scripting (XSS) supply-chain attack vectors.

• The Solution: Enforce strict Subresource Integrity (SRI) checks on script injection. Configure a robust Content Security Policy (CSP) that restricts script execution origins exclusively to authenticated enterprise asset domains.
What’s Coming Next
Now that our application can safely resolve and load arbitrary tenant features across isolated networks without polluting the baseline bundle size, we run into our next structural bottleneck: routing. How do we handle navigation spaces when every tenant demands entirely unique page paths, nested structures, and url schemas?
In Series #4: Tenant-Aware Routing Without Hardcoding, we will explore how to construct dynamic, schema-driven routing trees that map to variables provided entirely at runtime.
